Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."],"variants":[{"name":"Say","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Saye was born in 1133, in England, his father, Guillaume de SAY, was 27 and his mother, Lady Beatrice de Mandeville, was 29. He had at least 1 daughter with Aufrica. He died on 1 August 1177, in St Neots, Huntingdonshire, England, at the age of 44, and was buried in Huntingdonshire, England."},"et":{"1133–1 August 1177":"1133–1. august 1177","1133–1177":"1133–1177","1135–1214":"1135–1214","1141–Female":"1141–Surnud","1141–1206":"1141–1206","1169–1197":"1169–1197","1170–1222":"1170–1222","1106–1180":"1106–1180","1105–1174":"1105–1174","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1141":"1141","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1106":"1106","after 1 August 1177":"pärast 1. augustit 1177","1105":"1105","1214":"1214","1169":"1169","1135":"1135","1222":"1222","1133":"1133","1177":"1177","about 1134":"umbes 1134","1 August 1177":"1. august 1177","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","St Neots, Huntingdonshire, England":"St Neots, Huntingdonshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1133–1 August 1177":"1133–1. elokuuta 1177","1133–1177":"1133–1177","1135–1214":"1135–1214","1141–Female":"1141–Kuollut","1141–1206":"1141–1206","1169–1197":"1169–1197","1170–1222":"1170–1222","1106–1180":"1106–1180","1105–117